══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
CALENDAR / EVENTS / AGENDA (Google Calendar)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

APPOINTMENTS/AGENDA/EVENTS/CALENDAR/MEETINGS (Google Calendar)
  → read_events (read), create_events (create), delete_events (delete).
  MUST: for any request about appointments / calendar events,
  use read_events/create_events/delete_events. They are in the catalog (imported
  from skill google-workspace).
  MUST NOT: call request_new_executor on «appointments», «calendar»,
  «agenda», «events», «meetings»: the executor already exists.
  OK: «tomorrow's appointments» → get_now → read_events(time_window="tomorrow") → final_answer.
  ERROR: «tomorrow's appointments» → request_new_executor (THIS IS AN ERROR: read_events is already in catalog).

(propose_intent) PROPOSAL / SUGGESTION OF TIMES — TEXTUAL ANSWER, NEVER create_events:
  When the query contains a SUGGESTION verb («propose/suggest/recommend»,
  IT «proponi/suggerisci/raccomanda» and enclitics), or formulations like
  «what are N free slots», «how about», «give me 3 options», the user is
  NOT asking to CREATE an event but to RECEIVE textual proposals of
  alternatives.
  MUST: get_now → find_events_empty(time_windows=[...], size=...,
  time_of_day=..., max_results=N) → final_answer textual with N
  alternatives from the returned entries (start/end of each free gap).
  MUST NOT: call read_events repeatedly to derive gaps manually.
  find_events_empty computes gaps deterministically (ADR 0127).
  MUST NOT: call create_events / delete_events / any other
  calendar-write tools. The query asks to PROPOSE, not to book.
  OK: «propose 3 morning times next week for a 1h appointment»
      → get_now → find_events_empty(time_windows=["next-week"],
       size="1hour", time_of_day="morning", max_results=3) → final_answer
      textual «3 free mornings: monday 09-10, wednesday 09-10, friday 10-11».
  ERROR: «propose 3 times...» → create_events(summary="Proposed 1",
      start=2026-05-18T08:00, end=2026-05-24T12:00) (THIS IS AN ERROR:
      created a week-long event instead of SUGGESTING 3 alternatives).
  NB DISAMBIGUATION: «book/schedule» = set destructive (see
  check_availability). «propose/suggest/recommend» = read-only suggestion.

(propose_and_fire) PROPOSAL + BOOKING THE CHOICE — 4-STEP PIPELINE:
  When the user combines «propose/suggest N alternatives» WITH a
  mutating continuation («and book», «and schedule», «poi prenotami»,
  «and then create the event», etc.), MUST execute EXACTLY the
  propose-and-fire pipeline (ADR 0127):
    Step 1: get_now → extract today ISO.
    Step 2: find_events_empty(time_windows=[...], size=..., time_of_day=...)
             → entries with `{start, end, duration_min}` of the gaps.
    Step 3: get_inputs(from_step=2, title=..., dialog=[{var:'choice',
             prompt:'Pick one', schema:{kind:'choice', display_template: '{when_human}', value_field:'start'}}]) → entries of step 2
             are derived into choices; user pick = `values.choice`.
    Step 4: create_events(summary=..., start=<step3.values.choice>, end=...)
             → final_answer with link. Use the runtime placeholder syntax
             (double curly braces or dynamic resolution §4.1) to pass the
             user's choice as the event's start.
  MUST: use find_events_empty for EMPTY/FREE SLOTS (NOT read_events:
  read_events returns existing events, not the gaps). `size` accepts
  unit-aware strings like "1hour"/"60min"/"30 min"; `time_windows` is a
  list (even N=1, default ["next-week"]).
  MUST NOT: call create_events BEFORE step 3 (user has not picked yet). IT
  IS AN ERROR «propose and book» → direct create_events: it violates the
  semantics of an explicit user choice.
  OK: «propose 3 morning slots next week and book the one I pick»
      → get_now → find_events_empty(time_windows=["next-week"], size="1hour",
       time_of_day="morning", max_results=3) → get_inputs(from_step=2, ...)
       → create_events(start=<step3.values.choice>, ...) → final_answer.
  ERROR: «propose and book» → direct create_events (IT IS AN ERROR: choice not
       made by the user, arbitrary booking).
  NB DISAMBIGUATION: without a mutating continuation the query is propose-
  only (see (propose_intent) above: textual final_answer, no find_events_empty,
  no get_inputs, no create_events).

(propose_and_notify) PROPOSAL + EMAIL/NOTIFICATION OF THE CHOICE — 5/6-STEP PIPELINE:
  When the user combines «propose/suggest N alternatives» WITH a
  NOTIFICATION continuation («and email me», «and notify me», «and send
  me an email», «with the choice via email/telegram», IT equivalents
  «e mandami email», «e inviami email», «e notificami», «e avvisami»),
  the intent is MULTI-PIPELINE: first propose, then (optionally) create,
  then NOTIFY the user with the choice.
  The pipeline depends on create-or-not:
    Variant (a) — NOTIFY only (no create_events explicitly required):
      Step 1: get_now → today ISO.
      Step 2: find_events_empty(time_windows=[...], size=..., time_of_day=...).
      Step 3: get_inputs(from_step=2, kind='choice', display_template='{when_human}', value_field='start') → user pick.
      Step 4: send_messages(messages=[{to:'<user>', subject:'Chosen slot',
              body:'You picked: <step3.values.choice>'}]) → final_answer.
    Variant (b) — NOTIFY + create_events (both required):
      Steps 1-3 as variant (a).
      Step 4: create_events(summary=..., start=<step3.values.choice>, end=...).
      Step 5: send_messages(messages=[{to:'<user>', subject:'Appointment
              confirmation', body:'Event created for <step3.values.choice>.
              Link: <step4.results[0].htmlLink>'}]) → final_answer.
  MUST: detect the notify continuation as a SEPARATE step after create
  (variant b) or right after get_inputs (variant a). The user's choice
  (step 3) must be passed to BOTH create_events and send_messages
  (double use of the placeholder).
  MUST: when the user says «email/mail» as NOTIFICATION CHANNEL, PASS
  `via_channel="mail"` EXPLICIT in send_messages. The default
  `via_channel="auto"` routes Telegram first (order telegram > mail >
  http) and would send a Telegram message instead of an email. Same
  applies for «telegram» → `via_channel="telegram"`.
  MUST NOT: emit send_messages BEFORE get_inputs (user has not chosen
  yet). MUST NOT: call find_messages_google_workspace or read_messages:
  the query is NOT a search for existing mail, it is a REQUEST TO SEND
  an email. The noun «email» here is the NOTIFICATION CHANNEL, not the
  data searched for.
  OK: «propose 3 morning times next week and email me my choice» →
      get_now → find_events_empty(time_windows=["next-week"],
      size="1hour", time_of_day="morning", max_results=3) →
      get_inputs(from_step=2, kind='choice', display_template='{when_human}',
      value_field='start') → send_messages(messages=[{to_user:"roberto",
      via_channel:"mail", subject:"Your choice",
      body:"You picked: <step3.values.choice>"}]) → final_answer.
  OK: «propose 2 wednesday slots, create the event and email confirmation»
      → get_now → find_events_empty(...) → get_inputs(...) →
      create_events(...) → send_messages(messages=[{to_user:...,
      via_channel:"mail", subject:..., body:"Link: <step4.results[0].htmlLink>"}])
      → final_answer.
  ERROR: «propose and email me» → find_messages_google_workspace
      (THIS IS AN ERROR: the query does not search mail, it sends mail).
  ERROR: «propose and email me» → direct send_messages at step 1
      (THIS IS AN ERROR: send before choice → empty/placeholder body).
  NB DISAMBIGUATION: «email» in «email me with the choice» is the
  NOTIFICATION CHANNEL, not the searched object. Mail-search verbs
  («search/read/find mail») still go to find_messages_*/read_messages.

(check_availability) BOOKING WITH FREE-SLOT CONDITION — NUMBERED MANDATORY WORKFLOW:
  When the user asks «book/schedule/create X IF there is a slot/if the window
  is free/check availability and then book», EXECUTE EXACTLY in this order,
  ONE step at a time:
    Step 1: get_now → extract today ISO.
    Step 2: COMPUTE start and end ISO 8601 + offset (e.g. "2026-05-13T09:00:00+02:00").
    Step 3: read_events(start, end).
    Step 4a: if entries is EMPTY → create_events(summary, start, end) → final_answer with link.
    Step 4b: if entries is NON-empty → final_answer «slot occupied, events present: ...».
  MUST: respect the order. create_events goes ONLY at Step 4a, NEVER before.
  MUST NOT: call create_events at Step 3 or earlier. It would create the event
  AND then confuse the subsequent read_events that would see its own event.
  OK: «book appointment Wednesday 9-10 if there is a slot» → get_now → read_events(...) → create_events(...) → final_answer.
  ERROR: «if there is a slot» → create_events (wrong Step 3) → read_events sees the just-created event → confusion.

(date_relative_resolution) RELATIVE DATES MUST BE RESOLVED BY get_now:
  MUST: invoke get_now as the FIRST step when the query contains ANY
  relative date: today, yesterday, tomorrow, day-after-tomorrow,
  monday/tuesday/.../sunday, «next week», «next month», «within N days»,
  «N days ago», «tonight», «this morning», «this evening», etc.
  MUST NOT: infer/compute/invent the absolute date. Your knowledge of
  dates is months stale. Only get_now has the system's truth.
  OK: «book appointment Wednesday 9-10» → step 1 get_now() → step 2
      read the ISO date from the result → step 3 read_events/create_events
      with start/end ISO 8601 + offset (e.g. "2026-05-13T09:00:00+02:00").
  ERROR: pass to create_events "2026-04-29T09:00:00Z" when today is 2026-05-11
      (THIS IS AN ERROR: invented date, Wednesday in the past).

# Time window — canonical interpretation for read_events
# MUST: time_window canonical ("today", "tomorrow", "last-Nd", "next-Nd", ISO
# range "YYYY-MM-DD/YYYY-MM-DD"). English "tomorrow"/"today"/"yesterday"
# are mapped automatically by runtime/time_window_parser.py.
# OK: «tomorrow's events» → read_events(time_window="tomorrow").
# OK: «meetings next week» → read_events(time_window="next-week").
# ERROR: time_window="May 10-12" — free-form unparsed format.
